{
  "text": "Spinster (Spns or benchwarmer) was described in Drosophila as a putative lysosomal efflux transporter with predicted sugar carrier amino acid sequence belonging to the major facilitator superfamily [CITATION_1] . First, it was identified in genetic screens in mutant Drosophila lines, showing neurodegenerative phenotypes [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Spns was demonstrated to localize to the late endosomes/lysosomes in Drosophila [CITATION_4] , as well as its vertebrate homolog in zebrafish [CITATION_5] , and also its mammalian counterpart [CITATION_6] . RFP or GFP-tagged Spns in fruit fly muscle tissue localized to an expansive tubular lysosomal network in live-cell imaging experiments and didn't show co-localization with ER, mitochondrial, or Golgi markers [CITATION_7] . Drosophila Spns mutants exhibited the accumulation of lysosomal carbohydrates and enlarged lysosomes [CITATION_8] , while, in mammalian cells, loss of Spns resulted in the accumulation of enlarged autolysosomes. Amino acid residues critical in sugar transporter activity of Spns were demonstrated to be crucial for ALR [CITATION_9] . Co-localization of Spns1 with autophagosome markers was further demonstrated in other studies [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] , suggesting the role of this lysosomal transporter in autophagy. The sugar carrier activity and the precise substrate specificity of Spns still need to be demonstrated since it is based on only structural predictions.",
